Decision Support System Output:
Triage Complete
Triage Date: 12/05/2025, 01:40 PM
Triage Note:
Decision Support Tool Used: ClearTriage
Protocol Used: Chest Pain
Protocol-Based Disposition: See Provider within 24 Hours
Video visit offered and caller declined
Positive Triage Question:
* [1] Patient says chest pain feels exactly the same as previously diagnosed
"heartburn" AND [2] describes burning in chest AND [3] accompanying sour taste
in mouth
Care Advice Discussed:
* Reasons To Call Back
- Difficulty breathing or unusual sweating occurs
- Chest pain increases in frequency, duration or severity
- Chest pain lasts over 5 minutes
- You become worse
Negative Triage Questions:
* SEVERE difficulty breathing (e.g., struggling for each breath, speaks in
single words)
* Difficult to awaken or acting confused (e.g., disoriented, slurred speech)
* Shock suspected (e.g., cold/pale/clammy skin, too weak to stand, low BP,
rapid pulse)
* Passed out (e.g., fainted, lost consciousness, blacked out and was not
responding)
* [1] Chest pain lasts > 5 minutes AND [2] age > 44
* [1] Chest pain lasts > 5 minutes AND [2] age > 30 AND [3] one or more
cardiac risk factors (e.g., diabetes, high blood pressure, high cholesterol,
obesity with BMI 30 or higher, smoker, or strong family history of heart
disease)
* [1] Chest pain lasts > 5 minutes AND [2] history of heart disease (i.e.,
angina, heart attack, heart failure, bypass surgery, takes nitroglycerin)
* [1] Chest pain lasts > 5 minutes AND [2] described as crushing,
pressure-like, or heavy
* Heart beating < 50 beats per minute OR > 140 beats per minute
* Visible sweat on face or sweat dripping down face
* Sounds like a life-threatening emergency to the triager
* SEVERE chest pain
* [1] Chest pain (or "angina") comes and goes AND [2] is happening more often
(increasing in frequency) or getting worse (increasing in severity)
(Exception: Chest pains that last only a few seconds.)
* Pain also in shoulder(s) or arm(s) or jaw (Exception: Pain is clearly made
worse by movement.)
* Difficulty breathing
* Coughing up blood
* Cocaine use within last 3 days
* Major surgery in past month
* Hip or leg fracture (broken bone) in past month (or had cast on leg or ankle
in past month)
* Illness requiring prolonged bedrest in past month (e.g., immobilization,
long hospital stay)
* Long-distance travel in past month (e.g., car, bus, train, plane; with trip
lasting 6 or more hours)
* History of prior "blood clot" in leg or lungs (i.e., deep vein thrombosis,
pulmonary embolism)
* History of inherited increased risk of blood clots (e.g., Factor 5 Leiden,
Anti-thrombin 3, Protein C or Protein S deficiency, Prothrombin mutation)
* Cancer treatment in past six months (or has cancer now)
* Taking a deep breath makes pain worse
* [1] Chest pain lasts > 5 minutes AND [2] occurred in past 3 days (72 hours)
(Exception: Feels exactly the same as previously diagnosed heartburn and has
accompanying sour taste in mouth.)
* Patient sounds very sick or weak to the triager
* [1] Chest pain lasts > 5 minutes AND [2] occurred > 3 days ago (72 hours)
AND [3] NO chest pain or cardiac symptoms now
* [1] Chest pain lasts < 5 minutes AND [2] NO chest pain or cardiac symptoms
(e.g., breathing difficulty, sweating) now (Exception: Chest pains that last
only a few seconds.)
* Fever > 100.4 F (38.0 C)
* Rash in same area as pain (may be described as "small blisters")
-----------------

section.title: Medications: VA Dispensed and Non-VA Documented (Obtained Outside VA)

paragraph.content: Section Date Range: 1) prescriptions processed by a VA pharmacy in the last 15 months, and 2) all medications recorded in the VA medical record as "non-VA medications". Pharmacy terms refer to VA pharmacy's work on prescriptions. VA patients are advised to take their medications as instructed by their health care team. The data comes from all VA treatment facilities.

text.paragraph: Glossary of Pharmacy Terms:Active = A prescription that can be filled at the local VA pharmacy. Active: On Hold = An active prescription that will not be filled until pharmacy resolves the issue. Active: Parked = A VA Prescription that is on file at VA Pharmacy and available for you to submit a fill request. This prescription may or may not have been previously filled. This prescription has been ordered by your VA provider but will not be sent to you until you request that it is filled. You may request this medication using MyHealtheVet, Rx Refill mobile app, VA phone service or mail in refills. Active: Susp = An active prescription that is not scheduled to be filled yet. Clinic Order = A medication received during a visit to a VA clinic or emergency department (**currently not available**). Discontinued = A prescription stopped by a VA provider. It is no longer available to be filled. Expired = A prescription which is too old to fill. This does not refer to the expiration date of the medication in the container. Non-VA = A medication that came from someplace other than a VA pharmacy. This may be a prescription from either the VA or other providers that was filled outside the VA. Or, it may be an over the counter (OTC), herbal, dietary supplement or sample medication. Pending = This prescription order has been sent to the Pharmacy for review and is not ready yet. Transferred = A prescription moved to VA's new electronic health record. This prescription may also be described as "Discontinued" on medication lists from your healthcare team. Take your medications as prescribed by your healthcare team.

Specimen Type: FECES
Comment: The Biofire GI panel is indicated as an aid in the diagnosis of specific agents of gastrointestinal illness and results are meant to be used in conjunction with other clinical, laboratory, and epidemiological data. Positive results do not rule out co-infection with organisms not included in the Biofire GI Panel. The agent detected may not be the definite cause of the disease. A negative Biofire GI Panel result does not exclude the possibility of gastrointestinal infection. The performance of this test has not been established for patients without signs and symptoms of gastrointestinal illness. Some organisms may be carried asymptomatically. Detection of organism targets does not imply that the corresponding organisms are infectious or are the causative agents for clinical symptoms. This test has not been established for monitoring treatment of infection. This test only detects Campylobacter jejuni, C. coli, and C. upsaliensis. Additional testing is required to detect other Campylobacter species that may be present in stool specimens. Recent oral administration of a Rotavirus A vaccine may cause positive results.
